00:10:09.240 --> 00:10:13.520
that's crazy. Uh if you're not using uh

00:10:12.280 --> 00:10:15.360
if you're building a front-end app and

00:10:13.520 --> 00:10:17.240
you're not giving it the LLM access to

00:10:15.360 --> 00:10:19.040
the browser so it can look around,

00:10:17.240 --> 00:10:21.120
absolutely needs that.

00:10:19.040 --> 00:10:23.240
And you obviously also need automated

00:10:21.120 --> 00:10:26.080
tests.

00:10:23.240 --> 00:10:28.120
And one sort of

00:10:26.080 --> 00:10:30.440
thing I notice here is that even with

00:10:28.120 --> 00:10:32.400
these feedback loops, the LLM doesn't

00:10:30.440 --> 00:10:34.680
use them very well. It doesn't kind of

00:10:32.400 --> 00:10:35.760
like get the most out of its feedback

00:10:34.680 --> 00:10:38.160
loops in the way that a veteran

00:10:35.760 --> 00:10:40.720
developer would. And so it does what it

00:10:38.160 --> 00:10:42.520
tends to do is just does way too much at

00:10:40.720 --> 00:10:44.280
once. It will produce like a huge

00:10:42.520 --> 00:10:45.280
amounts of code and then think, "Oh, I

00:10:44.280 --> 00:10:47.040
should probably type check that

00:10:45.280 --> 00:10:48.880
actually." Or I should uh you know,

00:10:47.040 --> 00:10:50.560
maybe check a test on that or maybe do

00:10:48.880 --> 00:10:52.520
something like that.

00:10:50.560 --> 00:10:53.960
And this in the Pragmatic Programmer

00:10:52.520 --> 00:10:56.400
they describe as outrunning your

00:10:53.960 --> 00:10:58.240
headlights. It's essentially driving too

00:10:56.400 --> 00:11:00.960
fast because

00:10:58.240 --> 00:11:02.040
the rate of feedback is your speed

00:11:00.960 --> 00:11:03.600
limit.

00:11:02.040 --> 00:11:05.240
The rate of feedback is your speed

00:11:03.600 --> 00:11:07.520
limit, which means that you should be

00:11:05.240 --> 00:11:09.880
testing as you go, taking small

00:11:07.520 --> 00:11:11.920
deliberate steps. And the AI by default

00:11:09.880 --> 00:11:14.880
is really not very good at that.

00:11:11.920 --> 00:11:16.560
So, skill number three is TDD.

00:11:14.880 --> 00:11:17.880
You should be using test-driven

00:11:16.560 --> 00:11:21.680
development

00:11:17.880 --> 00:11:24.040
because TDD forces the LLM to

00:11:21.680 --> 00:11:27.120
really take small steps. You create a

00:11:24.040 --> 00:11:29.040
test first, you make that test pass, and

00:11:27.120 --> 00:11:32.280
then you refactor the code to make it

00:11:29.040 --> 00:11:33.960
nicer and consider the design.

00:11:32.280 --> 00:11:36.280
The issue here

00:11:33.960 --> 00:11:38.800
is that testing is really hard.

00:11:36.280 --> 00:11:41.560
Testing has always been hard.

00:11:38.800 --> 00:11:43.280
And the reason for that

00:11:41.560 --> 00:11:44.960
is there are a ton

00:11:43.280 --> 00:11:46.760
of different decisions you need to make

00:11:44.960 --> 00:11:48.960
when you write a test.

00:11:46.760 --> 00:11:50.520
You need to figure out how big a unit do

00:11:48.960 --> 00:11:52.000
you want to test?

00:11:50.520 --> 00:11:54.000
You need to figure out what to mock. You

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:55.680
need to figure out what behaviors do you

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:56.680
even want to test in the first place?

00:11:55.680 --> 00:11:58.360
And all of these decisions are

00:11:56.680 --> 00:12:00.920
dependent. So, if you are testing a

00:11:58.360 --> 00:12:03.000
really big unit like an entire uh

00:12:00.920 --> 00:12:04.520
massive application, then it might be

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:06.760
quite flaky. You might not want to test

00:12:04.520 --> 00:12:08.360
that many behaviors. You know, if you

00:12:06.760 --> 00:12:09.760
only test this unit, you need to mock

00:12:08.360 --> 00:12:11.240
this unit, you know. It's all

00:12:09.760 --> 00:12:12.720
interlinked. And I've been thinking

00:12:11.240 --> 00:12:15.160
about this for years, for my entire

00:12:12.720 --> 00:12:17.720
development career.

00:12:15.160 --> 00:12:20.760
And what we notice is that good

00:12:17.720 --> 00:12:22.640
codebases are easy codebases to test.

00:12:20.760 --> 00:12:24.040
Right? So, here we're starting to get

00:12:22.640 --> 00:12:26.120
back to the idea of code being

00:12:24.040 --> 00:12:27.880
important. It's that the better your

00:12:26.120 --> 00:12:31.640
codebase is, the better your feedback

00:12:27.880 --> 00:12:33.200
loops are because you're able to um

00:12:31.640 --> 00:12:35.560
give better feedback to the LLM, it

00:12:33.200 --> 00:12:37.000
produces better code.

00:12:35.560 --> 00:12:38.800
And so I thought, what does a good

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:41.080
codebase, what does a testable codebase

00:12:38.800 --> 00:12:42.440
look like? Again, we go to John

00:12:41.080 --> 00:12:45.280
Ousterhout. [clears throat]

00:12:42.440 --> 00:12:47.920
He talks about having deep modules in

00:12:45.280 --> 00:12:50.280
your codebase. Not shallow modules, not

00:12:47.920 --> 00:12:52.440
lots of modules that expose type kind of

00:12:50.280 --> 00:12:54.960
um lots of functions.

00:12:52.440 --> 00:12:57.480
They should be relatively few large deep

00:12:54.960 --> 00:12:59.480
modules with simple interfaces.

00:12:57.480 --> 00:13:01.400
Let's compare them quickly.

00:12:59.480 --> 00:13:04.040
Deep modules, lots of functionality

00:13:01.400 --> 00:13:05.640
hidden behind a simple interface. Hiding

00:13:04.040 --> 00:13:06.960
the complexity.

00:13:05.640 --> 00:13:08.080
You can look inside the deep module if

00:13:06.960 --> 00:13:10.000
you want to, but you don't need to. You

00:13:08.080 --> 00:13:12.320
can just use the interface. Shallow

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:13.880
modules, not much functionality, complex

00:13:12.320 --> 00:13:15.200
interface.

00:13:13.880 --> 00:13:16.440
And

00:13:15.200 --> 00:13:18.360
I'll just wait for you to take the

00:13:16.440 --> 00:13:19.920
photos.

00:13:18.360 --> 00:13:22.280
Shallow modules in a codebase kind of

00:13:19.920 --> 00:13:24.839
look like this, where you have a ton of

00:13:22.280 --> 00:13:26.839
different tiny little blobs that the AI

00:13:24.839 --> 00:13:29.200
has to walk through and navigate. And

00:13:26.839 --> 00:13:30.960
this is really hard for the AI to

00:13:29.200 --> 00:13:32.320
explore actually.

00:13:30.960 --> 00:13:33.960
And so often what you'll see is if you

00:13:32.320 --> 00:13:35.560
have a codebase like this, which AI is

00:13:33.960 --> 00:13:36.520
really good at creating codebases like

00:13:35.560 --> 00:13:38.560
this,

00:13:36.520 --> 00:13:40.160
is that you'll have a situation where AI

00:13:38.560 --> 00:13:42.400
doesn't understand what your code is

00:13:40.160 --> 00:13:45.080
doing. It will attempt to explore the

00:13:42.400 --> 00:13:47.280
code, but because it's poorly laid out,

00:13:45.080 --> 00:13:49.240
filled with shallow modules, it doesn't

00:13:47.280 --> 00:13:50.880
maybe get to the right module in time or

00:13:49.240 --> 00:13:52.120
doesn't understand all the dependencies,

00:13:50.880 --> 00:13:53.720
all that stuff. It doesn't understand

00:13:52.120 --> 00:13:54.960
your code.

00:13:53.720 --> 00:13:57.960
And so what does a

00:13:54.960 --> 00:14:00.280
codebase full of deep modules look like?

00:13:57.960 --> 00:14:02.200
Well, it looks like this.

00:14:00.280 --> 00:14:04.600
Where it's the same code, but it's just

00:14:02.200 --> 00:14:08.560
structured inside boundaries, where you

00:14:04.600 --> 00:14:10.400
have these interfaces on the top.

00:14:08.560 --> 00:14:12.240
And these interfaces, you should

00:14:10.400 --> 00:14:14.600
probably have a lot of control over them

00:14:12.240 --> 00:14:17.120
and design them really well. Otherwise,

00:14:14.600 --> 00:14:18.680
you know, AI might mess up the design.

00:14:17.120 --> 00:14:20.920
But the implementation, you can kind of

00:14:18.680 --> 00:14:23.600
leave that to the AI bit.

00:14:20.920 --> 00:14:26.800
So, how do you turn a codebase that

00:14:23.600 --> 00:14:29.120
looks like this into a codebase that

00:14:26.800 --> 00:14:31.200
looks like that?

00:14:29.120 --> 00:14:33.280
Well, I've got a skill for that. Improve

00:14:31.200 --> 00:14:35.680
codebase architecture. Turns out this is

00:14:33.280 --> 00:14:36.880
not It's it's quite complicated to do

00:14:35.680 --> 00:14:38.280
this, but it's a

00:14:36.880 --> 00:14:40.640
like a set of steps that you can

00:14:38.280 --> 00:14:42.839
reusably do again and again. You just

00:14:40.640 --> 00:14:44.400
sort of explore the codebase, look for

00:14:42.839 --> 00:14:45.640
opportunities where there's code that's

00:14:44.400 --> 00:14:47.880
kind of look um

00:14:45.640 --> 00:14:50.000
related, and wrap all of that in a deep

00:14:47.880 --> 00:14:52.000
module.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:54.640
And this is a testable codebase because

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:56.959
the boundaries around this code are so

00:14:54.640 --> 00:14:59.160
so simple. You test at the interface,

00:14:56.959 --> 00:15:00.480
you verify using that interface,

00:14:59.160 --> 00:15:04.240
and you're good to go. And so this is a

00:15:00.480 --> 00:15:06.480
codebase that rewards TDD.

00:15:04.240 --> 00:15:07.839
But how about failure mode number six?

00:15:06.480 --> 00:15:09.440
Which is your Okay, let's say your

00:15:07.839 --> 00:15:11.120
feedback loops are working. Let's say

00:15:09.440 --> 00:15:12.400
that things are kicking into gear.

00:15:11.120 --> 00:15:14.880
You're able to ship more code than you

00:15:12.400 --> 00:15:16.520
ever have before, but your brain can't

00:15:14.880 --> 00:15:18.560
keep up.

00:15:16.520 --> 00:15:20.440
Right? Uh raise your hand if you've felt

00:15:18.560 --> 00:15:22.320
more tired than you have ever before in

00:15:20.440 --> 00:15:25.160
your development career.

00:15:22.320 --> 00:15:27.680
Yeah, me too. It's knackering.

00:15:25.160 --> 00:15:30.600
And I think that this is a codebase that

00:15:27.680 --> 00:15:32.320
actually makes it harder for your brain

00:15:30.600 --> 00:15:33.520
because you, as well as the AI, need to

00:15:32.320 --> 00:15:34.800
keep all of that information in your

00:15:33.520 --> 00:15:38.320
head.

00:15:34.800 --> 00:15:40.760
Whereas this, not only is it simpler

00:15:38.320 --> 00:15:42.720
for you to read and understand, it also

00:15:40.760 --> 00:15:45.560
means you can kind of treat these

00:15:42.720 --> 00:15:47.360
modules, or these deep modules, as gray

00:15:45.560 --> 00:15:49.040
boxes.

00:15:47.360 --> 00:15:50.120
You can kind of say,

00:15:49.040 --> 00:15:52.200
"Okay,

00:15:50.120 --> 00:15:53.720
I'm going to just design the interface,

00:15:52.200 --> 00:15:57.000
but I'm not going to worry too much or

00:15:53.720 --> 00:15:58.520
not review the implementation too much."

00:15:57.000 --> 00:15:59.400
You can do this obviously with uh things

00:15:58.520 --> 00:16:01.600
that are less critical in your

00:15:59.400 --> 00:16:03.640
application. Can't do this with uh you

00:16:01.600 --> 00:16:05.920
know, various things like finance or

00:16:03.640 --> 00:16:07.720
whatever, but in many many modules in

00:16:05.920 --> 00:16:09.280
your app, you don't need to think about

00:16:07.720 --> 00:16:11.240
the implementation too much as long as

00:16:09.280 --> 00:16:13.079
you have a testable boundary outside the

00:16:11.240 --> 00:16:14.560
module, and as long as you understand

00:16:13.079 --> 00:16:17.280
its purpose and can design it from the

00:16:14.560 --> 00:16:19.280
outside. I have found this has really

00:16:17.280 --> 00:16:21.280
saved my brain because I can just go,

00:16:19.280 --> 00:16:23.000
"Okay, the AI, I'll let you handle

00:16:21.280 --> 00:16:24.040
what's inside the big blob. I'm just

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:26.000
going to test from the outside and

00:16:24.040 --> 00:16:27.760
verify it."

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:32.000
So, that's tip number five. Design the

00:16:27.760 --> 00:16:34.079
interface, delegate the implementation.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:35.320
But this means that whenever we're

00:16:34.079 --> 00:16:37.680
touching the code, whenever we're

00:16:35.320 --> 00:16:39.360
planning stuff, we need to think about

00:16:37.680 --> 00:16:41.400
and be aware of the modules in our

00:16:39.360 --> 00:16:43.560
application. We need to know that map

00:16:41.400 --> 00:16:45.720
really well. It needs to be part of our

00:16:43.560 --> 00:16:47.959
ubiquitous language. We need to build it

00:16:45.720 --> 00:16:50.560
into our planning skills as well. So, my

00:16:47.959 --> 00:16:52.000
write a PRD, inside the PRD I'm specific

00:16:50.560 --> 00:16:54.240
about the module changes and the

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:55.360
interfaces inside those modules, how

00:16:54.240 --> 00:16:57.160
they're being modified. I'm thinking

00:16:55.360 --> 00:16:58.760
about them all the time. And this comes

00:16:57.160 --> 00:17:01.360
from Kent Beck.

00:16:58.760 --> 00:17:02.720
Invest in the design of the system every

00:17:01.360 --> 00:17:03.920
day.

00:17:02.720 --> 00:17:06.679
And this is the core of it, right?

00:17:03.920 --> 00:17:08.560
Because specs to code, we are not

00:17:06.679 --> 00:17:10.720
investing in the design of the system.

00:17:08.560 --> 00:17:12.240
We are divesting from it. We're getting

00:17:10.720 --> 00:17:13.959
rid of that.

00:17:12.240 --> 00:17:16.320
Whereas this, I think, is absolutely

00:17:13.959 --> 00:17:16.320
key.

00:17:16.400 --> 00:17:19.880
And so

00:17:18.040 --> 00:17:21.600
code is not cheap. That's the message I

00:17:19.880 --> 00:17:23.439
want you to take away. Code is

00:17:21.600 --> 00:17:25.079
important.

00:17:23.439 --> 00:17:27.880
And if we think about AI as a really

00:17:25.079 --> 00:17:29.600
great on-the-ground programmer,

00:17:27.880 --> 00:17:32.080
a kind of tactical programmer, a

00:17:29.600 --> 00:17:35.520
sergeant on the ground making the code

00:17:32.080 --> 00:17:36.720
changes, you need someone above that.

00:17:35.520 --> 00:17:39.600
You need someone thinking on the

00:17:36.720 --> 00:17:41.280
strategic level. And that's you.

00:17:39.600 --> 00:17:43.560
And that requires software fundamental

00:17:41.280 --> 00:17:46.400
skills that we've been using for 20

00:17:43.560 --> 00:17:48.000
years, for longer.

00:17:46.400 --> 00:17:49.560
Now, if you were interested in any of

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:52.000
the skills I put up here, it's in the

00:17:49.560 --> 00:17:53.520
GitHub repo macpocockskills.

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:55.920
And if you're interested in the training

00:17:53.520 --> 00:17:57.600
that I do or any free stuff, I'm on

00:17:55.920 --> 00:17:59.600
YouTube, I'm on Twitter, but I'm also at

00:17:57.600 --> 00:18:01.000
aihero.dev, where I have a newsletter

00:17:59.600 --> 00:18:03.080
you can check out.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:05.640
Thank you so much. I hope that this

00:18:03.080 --> 00:18:06.440
gives you confidence in this new AI age

00:18:05.640 --> 00:18:07.840
that you can actually make a good

00:18:06.440 --> 00:18:09.277
impact.

00:18:07.840 --> 00:18:10.587
Thank you.

00:18:09.277 --> 00:18:12.607
>> [music]

00:18:10.587 --> 00:18:12.607
[applause]

